## Working in this repo

This repo follows a **worktree-based workflow**. The clone you're looking at — at `~/workspace/{{REPO_NAME}}/` — is the "main" worktree. It stays on the default branch and stays clean. All real feature work happens in **sibling worktrees** under `.worktrees/<branch>/`.

### Why

- The main checkout always reflects what's on the default branch, so it's safe to read, grep, and orient against.
- Multiple branches can be checked out simultaneously — useful when comparing two implementations, or when an interrupting bugfix needs its own clean tree.
- Each worktree gets its own `node_modules` / build artifacts, so switching branches never invalidates them.

### How

When starting feature work, defer to the **`jojo-skills:using-git-worktrees`** skill. Don't re-derive the workflow — that skill handles branch naming, directory placement, `.gitignore` verification, project setup, and baseline test runs. The short version:

```bash
git worktree add .worktrees/<branch-name> -b <branch-name>
cd .worktrees/<branch-name>
# ... do the work, commit, push, open PR ...
```

When the branch is merged or abandoned, clean up with `git worktree remove .worktrees/<branch-name>` — never `rm -rf` (that leaves dangling metadata in `.git/worktrees/`).

`.worktrees/` is gitignored — see `.gitignore`.

## Plans

Implementation plans live in `specs/`. New plans are authored with the **`jojo-skills:writing-plans`** skill. See `specs/README.md` for the convention.
